initial_story:
The National Police Air Service has shared a video of what it was like flying through Storm Gerrit's heavy winds, in a helicopter.

The footage, which was captured from inside the cockpit, shows the chopper rocking side to side, after being hit by winds of up to 80mph (128km/h).

Posting on X, formerly known as Twitter, the NPAS said "If you think it's windy down there, spare a thought for us up here in our flying washing machine".

The footage was filmed near Lea Valley reservoirs, North London.
stories: The camera shakes violently as the helicopter's rotors struggle to maintain lift, and the pilots' voices come through the intercom, steady and calm, but with a hint of concern. "We're going to need to adjust our altitude, we're getting too close to the trees," one of them says. The windshield is speckled with rain, and the trees below blur into a greenish-brown smear.

The pilot's words send a surge of adrenaline through the helicopter's occupant, and they grab the safety harness with a tight grip, their heart racing in sync with the helicopter's trembling frame. Despite the chaos outside, the interior of the aircraft remains remarkably tranquil, the soft hum of the instruments and the distant thrum of the engines providing a peculiar sense of serenity.

As the pilot's voice grows more urgent, the occupant's gaze darts out the window, taking in the swirling vortex of debris and flames, the very fabric of reality seeming to unravel outside the aircraft's protective shell. The heat and smoke wafting in through the open door creates a choking haze, and the occupant's mouth and nose sting from the acrid fumes.

With the pilot's words becoming almost indecipherable through the din of the wind and the engines roaring in protest, the occupant's eyes struggle to focus on the chaos beyond the wing, but a fleeting glimpse of a burning building, its windows shattered and its steel frame twisted and distorted, sears itself into their retina.

As the aircraft banks sharply to port, the occupant's gaze is jerked violently towards the inside of the plane, and for an instant, the sounds of the storm outside recede, replaced by the cacophony of screams and shouts of panic that erupt from the other passengers.

Some screams are shrill and piercing, while others are low and despairing, and in the midst of it all, a woman's voice rises above the din, her words pleading and urgent: "What's happening? What's happening?!" The occupant's eyes dart wildly around the cramped cabin, taking in the chaos and confusion, as the aircraft continues to plunge steeply through the turbulent air, throwing its occupants about like rag dolls.

The pilot's voice cracks through the intercom, his words a mixture of fear and desperation: "Mayday, mayday, we're experiencing extreme turbulence... cannot maintain altitude... cannot predict when or if we'll recover... stay seated, everyone, and prepare for impact!"

"Repeat, repeat, this is Flight 121, we're experiencing catastrophic failure of our right wing, it's shedding debris, I can see it coming loose... everyone, your lives are in imminent danger, we're going to make an emergency landing, but I warn you, it's not going to be pretty..."

"... Mayday, mayday, this is Flight 121, please respond with emergency services availability and estimated time of arrival, repeat, we are losing altitude at an alarming rate, and the pilots are having trouble maintaining control of the aircraft... we are sending out a locator beacon, please try to intercept... our transponder is malfunctioning, we're flying blind, and... oh God, we're hit! Our wing is gone, we're plummeting towards the ground, please, someone, get us out of this!"

"...Mayday, mayday, this is Flight 121, we're going down, we're going down, please, can anyone hear me? We're losing airspeed, we're falling, falling, falling, and... and... there's so much chaos up here, it's like we're in freefall, no control, no control... can anyone please, please respond, please help us, please..."

"Roger that, Flight 121, this is Air Traffic Control, we read you loud and clear. We're scrambling an emergency response team and vectoring in rescue assets. Can you give us your exact location and altitude? We have multiple radar contacts trying to lock onto you. Hang in there, help is on the way. Over."

"Roger that, Air Traffic Control. We're experiencing heavy turbulence and losing altitude rapidly. Our estimated location is coordinates 37.4220° N, 122.0840° W, and we're currently at an altitude of 5,000 feet. We have multiple system failures and are having trouble maintaining lift. Requesting immediate assistance. Over."
"Roger that, Delta Bravo. Can you confirm your last reported altitude and course? Are you experiencing any control issues? Can you give me a status update on the extent of the system failures? Over."

"This is Delta Bravo. Confirming my last reported altitude of 35,000 feet and course 270 degrees. I am experiencing control issues with the left aileron, and having difficulty maintaining level flight. The system failures are extensive, with multiple alerts for engine malfunctions and damage to the portside horizontal stabilizer. I'm making best efforts to stabilize the aircraft, but recommend immediate emergency descent to assess and address the situation further. Over."

"Roger that, Delta Bravo. This is Mission Control. We are verifying your altitude and course. Can you give me a more detailed description of the left aileron issue and what you've tried to compensate for it so far? Additionally, we'd like to clear up any confusion - is the control issue causing any oscillations or wobbles, or is it affecting only roll control? We are also sending a flight rescue package to your location, ETA five minutes. Recommend you prepare for descent and standby for further instructions. Over."

"Roger that, Mission Control. Delta Bravo copies. Left aileron issue is caused by restricted movement, about 30 degrees of play, which is causing a slight wobble during roll maneuvers. I've tried to compensate by adjusting the flight plan to use more precise turns and avoiding sudden movements. Oscillations or wobbles are present, but they're minor and stable so far. We've not noticed any significant degradation in roll control, but I'm monitoring it closely. Flight rescue package confirmed, ETA five minutes as reported. Preparing for descent and standing by for further instructions. Requesting clarification on the recommended descent path and any specific procedures to follow. Over."

"Roger that, Delta Bravo. Affirmative on flight plan adjustments. Recommend a 3-mile final approach, descending to 5,000 feet at 120 knots. Use GPS navigation to guide you to the nearest landing zone, and be prepared to adapt to changing wind conditions. As you descend, monitor your airspeed and adjust your rate of descent accordingly. Flight rescue party is on standby at the designated recovery site. Over."

"Roger, Delta Bravo. Understand and acknowledge all clearance details. Beginning descent at 15,000 feet, transitioning to GPS navigation. Airspeed is steady at 140 knots. Will monitor and adjust rate of descent as needed. Wind conditions currently at 180 degrees at 10 knots. Estimated touchdown time 10 minutes. Asking for status update on flight rescue party. Confirm they are on standby and aware of our estimated landing time. Over."

"Roger that, Delta Bravo. Acknowledge all clearance details. Status update on flight rescue party is as follows: they are en route to your estimated landing site and expect to be on standby in 5 minutes. Wind conditions remaining the same, and air traffic control has cleared you for approach. Descend at a rate of 1,000 feet per minute. Visual landing, runway 27 in sight. Estimate touchdown in 5 minutes. Any further updates on ETA or concerns please report. Over."

"Roger, Delta Bravo. Confirmed receipt of clearance details and status update. Beginning descent at 1,000 feet per minute, visual landing on runway 27. ETA touchdown remains 5 minutes. Requesting final approach navigation guidance. Any changes to wind conditions or air traffic control advisories please advise. Standing by. Over."

"Roger, Delta Bravo. Winds steady at 5 knots from 270 degrees, and slight turbulence expected 1 mile prior to touchdown. No changes to air traffic control advisories. Descending on a heading of 274 degrees. Requesting clearance for final approach and preparation for landing. Any further updates welcome. Over."

"Roger that, Delta Bravo. Clear for final approach and cleared for landing on Runway 27L. Winds remain steady at 5 knots from 270 degrees. Report established on localizer and begin aligning with the threshold. Approach control advising slight patch of fog at the threshold, expect some slight reduction in visibility. Over."

"Roger, Delta Bravo. Lining up on the localizer and aligning with the threshold. Expecting slight reduction in visibility due to fog, will report when passing through the patch. Also, requesting confirmation of the runway lighting status, specifically the distance markings. Over."

"Roger that, Delta Bravo. Can confirm runway lighting is normal, distance markings fully functional. Fog shouldn't affect them. Be advised, however, to increase descent rate slightly to ensure clearance above obstacles at the approach end. Ready for your descent and runway 22 approach. Over."
"Roger that, Air Traffic Control. Descent rate adjusted to compensate for obstacles. Requesting clearance to descend to 1,500 feet and turn to align with runway 22. Over."
"Roger, Cessna 12345. Clearance to descend to 1,500 feet and turn to align with runway 22 is granted. Report established on approach frequency. Contact me when cleared for landing. Over."
"Roger, Cessna 12345. Established on approach frequency and reporting established at 1,500 feet, aligned with runway 22. Request clearance for landing when ready. Over."
"Roger that, Cessna 12345. Cleared to land runway 22. Wind 230 at 5, visibility 3 miles, altimeter 29.90. Report landing and parking instructions when on the ground. Over."
"Cessna 12345, this is Ground Control. Landing and parking instructions are Bravo-1, taxi via Charlie to Echo-7, then turn left to A-Fuel. Report upon arrival. Over."
"Cessna 12345, roger that. Affirming Bravo-1, taxi via Charlie to Echo-7, then turn left to A-Fuel. Will report upon arrival. Over."
"Roger that, Cessna 12345. A-Fuel is currently unavailable due to maintenance. Please taxi via Charlie to Foxtrot instead and report when cleared for fueling. Over."
"Cessna 12345, Roger that. Understand maintenance on A-Fuel. Will taxi via Charlie to Foxtrot and report when cleared. Over."
"Cessna 12345, Affirmative. Cleared to taxi via Charlie to Foxtrot. Departure fuel dump still active, exercise caution. Report any traffic conflicts. Over."
"Roger that, Departure. Cleared to taxi, will exercise caution. Report any conflicts. Request permission to switch to Tower frequency once at holding point Foxtrot. Over."
" Roger that, Control. Be advised, Departure, will hold short of Foxtrot at runway centerline awaiting clearance for departure. Request update on other departures and approach traffic. Over."

"Roger that, Departure. Foxtrot at centerline, advise runway 27L is still active and expects a delay due to maintenance. Approach has reports of a Gulfstream taxiing onto runway 27R, ETA 5 minutes. Hold short for approximately 10 minutes, then clear for departure. Maintain frequency, over."

"Roger that, Departure. Wilco, holding short of runway 27L at centerline. Confirm Gulfstream's ETA 5 minutes and estimated time to clear for departure. Can you advise if this is a one-off or multiple arrivals on 27R, over."

"Roger, Departure. ETA for Gulfstream is confirmed at 5 minutes. I show multiple arrivals on 27R, with Flight 123 in sequence to depart next in approximately 10 minutes. Please clear for departure at that time, over."

"Roger that, departure. I read multiple arrivals on 27R and Flight 123 in sequence for departure in 10 minutes. Cleared for departure at that time. Confirm your departure frequency and squawk code, over."
"Roger that, tower. Departure frequency is 119.1 and squawk code is 4337. Affirming both, over."

"Affirmed, departing in five mikes. Outbound heading 270, estimating 10 miles east of Bravo Alpha at the initial navigational fix. Weather is mostly clear with a few cumulus clouds at 6,000 feet. Will climb to 12,000 feet over the terrain. Negative for any traffic in sight, over."

"Roger that, climbing to 12,000 feet as planned. Beginning descent as per routing. Estimated arrival Bravo Alpha, 4,000 feet, ETA 5 minutes. Visual inspection complete, no signs of damage. Cleared for landing, will make a straight in approach, over."
"Landing gear dropping, checking in at 3,000 feet, visual references are aligned. Beginning flaps 15, checking altimeter at 2,000 feet. Requesting permission to execute straight in approach, over."
"Roger that, runway 27 clear for straight in approach. Wind is at 230 at 10 knots. Contact approach control for further instructions, over."
"Affirmative, cleared for straight in approach on runway 27. Switching to approach control now. This is Delta One-Niner-Bravo reporting in with Delta Air Lines flight 123. Over."

"Delta One-Niner-Bravo, approach control, welcome to the visual approach. Descend and maintain 2,500, turn right heading 280. Runway 27, ILS active, report established on the localizer when able. Over."
"Delta One-Niner-Bravo, roger that, descend and maintain 2,500, turning right heading 280. Runway 27, ILS active, reporting established on the localizer, will advise when arrived. Over."
"Delta One-Niner-Bravo, understood, descending at 1,000 per minute, now at 3,000, turning right heading 280. Will be on localizer approach to Runway 27 in 5 minutes. Over."
"Delta One-Niner-Bravo, roger that, have you got the visual reference of the runway and the approach lights, over."

"Delta One-Niner-Bravo, affirmative, I've got a clear visual on the runway and the approach lights, and I'm on course for a straight-in approach to runway one-seven-left. Requesting clearance to descend to one thousand five hundred feet, over."
